</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Cross-sectional imaging techniques are playing an increasing role in the evaluation of suspected small-bowel disorders, and a growing awareness of the risks of ionizing radiation exposure has prompted the exploration of alternative imaging techniques. Advantages of magnetic resonance (MR) imaging include a lack of ionizing radiation, the ability to provide dynamic information regarding bowel distention and motility, improved soft-tissue contrast, and a relatively safe intravenous contrast agent profile. Limitations of MR imaging include cost, imager access, variability in examination quality, and lower spatial and temporal resolution compared with those of computed tomography (CT). MR imaging of the small bowel is indicated for patients with Crohn disease, those for whom exposure to radiation is a concern, those with contraindications to CT, and those with low-grade small-bowel obstruction. MR imaging may be performed with enterography or enteroclysis. In enterography, large volumes of fluid are ingested. Several different contrast agents may be used. These agents are classified according to their signal intensity on T1- and T2-weighted images. In enteroclysis, enteric contrast material is administered through a nasoenteric tube. Crohn disease is the primary indication for MR imaging of the small bowel because many patients require multiple follow-up examinations. Findings suggestive of active inflammation include bowel wall thickening and hyperenhancement, ulcerations, increased mesenteric vascularity, and perienteric inflammation. Complications are well depicted and may include penetrating disease and small-bowel obstruction.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095507">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095507">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g01x.jpeg" height="1446" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Unknown Crohn disease in a young pregnant woman who presented with abdominal pain and diarrhea. Axial balanced steady-state free precession (SSFP) MR image shows an intrauterine pregnancy (long arrow) and ileal thickening (short arrow). Note the irregular mucosal border, a finding consistent with ulcerations. Active inflammation is seen without the use of intravenous contrast material or exposure to ionizing radiation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f1-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g10a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1745" aria-labelledby="f10a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Mesenteric lymphadenopathy in a patient with Crohn disease. Coronal HASTE <b>(a)</b> and balanced SSFP <b>(b)</b> MR images show mesenteric adenopathy (arrowheads), which is much more conspicuous in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f10a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g10b.jpeg" height="1708" width="1710" aria-labelledby="f10b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Mesenteric lymphadenopathy in a patient with Crohn disease. Coronal HASTE <b>(a)</b> and balanced SSFP <b>(b)</b> MR images show mesenteric adenopathy (arrowheads), which is much more conspicuous in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f10b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g11a.jpeg" height="1252" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Mural stratification in two patients with Crohn disease. Coronal two-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(a)</b> and axial three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(b)</b> MR images obtained with fat suppression and intravenous contrast material show stratified bowel wall enhancement (arrows), a finding characteristic of active inflammation with a benign cause.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f11a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g11b.jpeg" height="1223" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Mural stratification in two patients with Crohn disease. Coronal two-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(a)</b> and axial three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(b)</b> MR images obtained with fat suppression and intravenous contrast material show stratified bowel wall enhancement (arrows), a finding characteristic of active inflammation with a benign cause.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f11b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g12a.jpeg" height="1084" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f12a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Homogeneous bowel wall enhancement. <b>(a)</b> Axial fat-suppressed two-dimensional gradient-echo MR image obtained with intravenous contrast material shows homogeneous hyperenhancement of the bowel wall (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed balanced SSFP MR image shows an area of high signal intensity (arrow) within the bowel wall, a finding suggestive of active inflammation or fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f12a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g12b.jpeg" height="1074" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f12b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Homogeneous bowel wall enhancement. <b>(a)</b> Axial fat-suppressed two-dimensional gradient-echo MR image obtained with intravenous contrast material shows homogeneous hyperenhancement of the bowel wall (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed balanced SSFP MR image shows an area of high signal intensity (arrow) within the bowel wall, a finding suggestive of active inflammation or fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f12b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g13a.jpeg" height="1430" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Submucosal fat deposit resulting from chronic bowel inflammation. Axial HASTE <b>(a)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(b)</b> MR images show submucosal fat deposition secondary to chronic inflammatory changes in the rectum (arrow). This stratified appearance should not be confused with that seen in the presence of active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f13a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g13b.jpeg" height="1425" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Submucosal fat deposit resulting from chronic bowel inflammation. Axial HASTE <b>(a)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(b)</b> MR images show submucosal fat deposition secondary to chronic inflammatory changes in the rectum (arrow). This stratified appearance should not be confused with that seen in the presence of active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f13b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g14a.jpeg" height="1416" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f14a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Mural thickening. Coronal balanced SSFP <b>(a)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced fat-suppressed three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(b)</b> MR images show irregular thickening (arrow in <b>a</b>) and increased enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>) of the wall of the neoterminal ileum, findings suggestive of active inflammation. The mural irregularity represents ulceration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f14a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g14b.jpeg" height="1426" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f14b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Mural thickening. Coronal balanced SSFP <b>(a)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced fat-suppressed three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(b)</b> MR images show irregular thickening (arrow in <b>a</b>) and increased enhancement (arrow in <b>b</b>) of the wall of the neoterminal ileum, findings suggestive of active inflammation. The mural irregularity represents ulceration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f14b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g15a.jpeg" height="1109" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f15a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Fibrostenotic Crohn disease. Axial balanced SSFP MR images without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat suppression show low-signal-intensity duodenal wall thickening (arrows) and proximal obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f15a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g15b.jpeg" height="1134" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f15b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Fibrostenotic Crohn disease. Axial balanced SSFP MR images without <b>(a)</b> and with <b>(b)</b> fat suppression show low-signal-intensity duodenal wall thickening (arrows) and proximal obstruction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f15b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g16a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1605" aria-labelledby="f16a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Ileocecal fistula. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> balanced SSFP MR images show a fluid-filled tubular structure (arrow) originating from the cecum and coursing parallel to the terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f16a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g16b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1628" aria-labelledby="f16b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Ileocecal fistula. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> balanced SSFP MR images show a fluid-filled tubular structure (arrow) originating from the cecum and coursing parallel to the terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f16b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g17x.jpeg" height="1586" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f17-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Complex internal bowel fistula. Coronal contrast-enhanced two-dimensional gradient-echo MR image shows a stellate pattern of bowel loop retraction to a central point (arrow), a finding associated with a complex internal fistula.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f17-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g18x.jpeg" height="1476" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f18-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Bowel obstruction in a patient with active Crohn disease. Coronal fat-suppressed three-dimensional gradient-echo MR image obtained with intravenous contrast material shows evidence of small-bowel obstruction due to active inflammation, with bowel dilatation (short arrow) proximal to an area of narrowing (long arrow). Associated bowel wall thickening and increased mucosal enhancement also are seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f18-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g19a.jpeg" height="1235" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f19a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Adhesions without obstruction. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial fat-suppressed balanced SSFP MR images show multiple distorted, tapered small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP MR image shows an adhesive band (arrow) causing retraction of a small-bowel loop, the sigmoid colon, and an ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f19a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g19b.jpeg" height="1234" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f19b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Adhesions without obstruction. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial fat-suppressed balanced SSFP MR images show multiple distorted, tapered small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP MR image shows an adhesive band (arrow) causing retraction of a small-bowel loop, the sigmoid colon, and an ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f19b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19c-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g19c.jpeg" height="1235" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f19c-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> Adhesions without obstruction. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial fat-suppressed balanced SSFP MR images show multiple distorted, tapered small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP MR image shows an adhesive band (arrow) causing retraction of a small-bowel loop, the sigmoid colon, and an ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f19c-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19d-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g19d.jpeg" height="1234" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f19d-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span> Adhesions without obstruction. <b>(a–c)</b> Axial fat-suppressed balanced SSFP MR images show multiple distorted, tapered small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP MR image shows an adhesive band (arrow) causing retraction of a small-bowel loop, the sigmoid colon, and an ovary.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f19d-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g02x.jpeg" height="1737" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Polyposis syndrome in a patient with Cowden disease. Coronal fat-suppressed three-dimensional gradient-echo MR image obtained with intravenous contrast material shows an enhancing jejunal polyp (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f2-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g20a.jpeg" height="1199" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f20a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Low-grade obstruction caused by adhesions. <b>(a)</b> Axial MR enterographic image shows a distorted small-bowel loop (arrow) in the right lower quadrant, without obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Axial image from follow-up MR enteroclysis with improved bowel distention (arrowhead) shows a persistent focal transition point (arrow) indicative of a proximal obstruction. These findings are suggestive of an adhesion, the presence of which was confirmed at laparoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f20a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g20b.jpeg" height="1201" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f20b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Low-grade obstruction caused by adhesions. <b>(a)</b> Axial MR enterographic image shows a distorted small-bowel loop (arrow) in the right lower quadrant, without obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Axial image from follow-up MR enteroclysis with improved bowel distention (arrowhead) shows a persistent focal transition point (arrow) indicative of a proximal obstruction. These findings are suggestive of an adhesion, the presence of which was confirmed at laparoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f20b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g03x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1622" aria-labelledby="f3-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Interloop abscess in a patient with Crohn disease. Coronal T2-weighted fat-suppressed two-dimensional balanced SSFP MR image obtained with negative enteric contrast material shows an interloop abscess (long arrow), which is easily distinguished from the fluid-filled bowel. The bowel lumen is dark, and mural inflammation is seen in adjacent small-bowel loops (short arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f3-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g04x.jpeg" height="1686" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Crohn ileocolitis. Coronal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed three-dimensional gradient-echo MR image obtained with intravenous contrast material shows a subtle area of increased mucosal enhancement in the ileum (short arrow) with no significant wall thickening, a finding consistent with mild inflammatory changes. Colonic inflammation also is seen (long arrow) because of antegrade filling.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f4-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g05x.jpeg" height="1242" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Crohn colitis. Axial three-dimensional gradient-echo MR image obtained with intravenous contrast material shows mucosal hyperenhancement and wall thickening in the colon (arrows), findings consistent with active inflammation. In this case, adequate colonic visualization was achieved because of antegrade filling.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f5-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g06a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1582" aria-labelledby="f6a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Cecal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP MR image shows an annular soft-tissue mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial intravenous contrast material–enhanced fat-suppressed three-dimensional gradient-echo MR image shows the soft-tissue mass (arrow) with homogeneous wall enhancement and adjacent adenopathy (arrowhead). An adenocarcinoma was found at subsequent colonoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f6a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g06b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1608" aria-labelledby="f6b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Cecal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP MR image shows an annular soft-tissue mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial intravenous contrast material–enhanced fat-suppressed three-dimensional gradient-echo MR image shows the soft-tissue mass (arrow) with homogeneous wall enhancement and adjacent adenopathy (arrowhead). An adenocarcinoma was found at subsequent colonoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f6b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g07x.jpeg" height="776" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Active Crohn disease. Dynamic axial contrast-enhanced three-dimensional gradient-echo MR images (left to right, top to bottom) show progressive rapid bowel wall enhancement within the first 70 seconds after injection of contrast material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f7-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g08x.jpeg" height="1330" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> The “comb” sign. Coronal balanced SSFP image shows engorgement of the vasa recta (arrows) with increased flow to the actively inflamed bowel segment, a finding known as the comb sign. This finding may be helpful for diagnosing active inflammation, especially in patients with a contraindication to the use of intravenous contrast material. Thickened bowel loops (arrowheads) also are visible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f8-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9a-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g09a.jpeg" height="1601" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9a-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Low-signal-intensity artifacts at HASTE imaging of the small bowel. <b>(a)</b> Coronal HASTE image obtained in a patient with an ileal carcinoid tumor shows multiple low-signal-intensity filling defects secondary to peristalsis within small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image shows an absence of flow void artifacts. <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP <b>(c)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(d)</b> MR images show a mass (arrow) with a mural location that helps differentiate it from the artifacts seen in <b>a</b>, which are more centrally located.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f9a-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9b-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g09b.jpeg" height="1590" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9b-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Low-signal-intensity artifacts at HASTE imaging of the small bowel. <b>(a)</b> Coronal HASTE image obtained in a patient with an ileal carcinoid tumor shows multiple low-signal-intensity filling defects secondary to peristalsis within small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image shows an absence of flow void artifacts. <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP <b>(c)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(d)</b> MR images show a mass (arrow) with a mural location that helps differentiate it from the artifacts seen in <b>a</b>, which are more centrally located.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f9b-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9c-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g09c.jpeg" height="1602" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9c-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Low-signal-intensity artifacts at HASTE imaging of the small bowel. <b>(a)</b> Coronal HASTE image obtained in a patient with an ileal carcinoid tumor shows multiple low-signal-intensity filling defects secondary to peristalsis within small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image shows an absence of flow void artifacts. <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP <b>(c)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(d)</b> MR images show a mass (arrow) with a mural location that helps differentiate it from the artifacts seen in <b>a</b>, which are more centrally located.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f9c-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9d-0291811" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095507/asset/images/g09oc08g09d.jpeg" height="1600" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9d-0291811" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span> Low-signal-intensity artifacts at HASTE imaging of the small bowel. <b>(a)</b> Coronal HASTE image obtained in a patient with an ileal carcinoid tumor shows multiple low-signal-intensity filling defects secondary to peristalsis within small-bowel loops (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image shows an absence of flow void artifacts. <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP <b>(c)</b> and intravenous contrast material–enhanced three-dimensional gradient-echo <b>(d)</b> MR images show a mass (arrow) with a mural location that helps differentiate it from the artifacts seen in <b>a</b>, which are more centrally located.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095507&amp;id=f9d-0291811">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0291811" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Brenner DJ, Hall EJ. Computed tomography: an increasing source of radiation exposure. <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2007;357:2277–2284.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMra072149">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18046031/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Computed+tomography%3A+an+increasing+source+of+radiation+exposure&amp;author=DJ+Brenner&amp;author=EJ+Hall&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;journal=N+Engl+J+Med&amp;pages=2277-2284&amp;doi=10.1056%2FNEJMra072149&amp;pmid=18046031">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0291811" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Fidler J. MR imaging of the small bowel. <em>Radiol Clin North Am</em> 2007;45:317–331.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rcl.2007.03.012">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.